{
  "answer": "**The Wanderer** (from *The Wanderer* in *Old English Elegies*): \"All that joy has perished!\"[^1]\n\n**Ghalib's persona** (from ghazal 70 in *Diwan-E-Ghalib*): \"A thousand wishes, each could make my spirit cease; / So many of my dreams came true, yet brought so little peace.\"[^2]\n\nBoth speakers would find the other's grief recognisable. The Wanderer, adrift in exile and haunted by vanished hall-joys and kinsmen despite the world's inevitable decay, mirrors Ghalib's endless desires that persist even after many are fulfilled, leaving no true peace. Each confronts sorrow's unyielding residue—loss for one, insatiable longing for the other—in a world of loaned wealth and fleeting bonds.[^3][^4]\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 70 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/#p-fcc8ca).\n\n[^3]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^4]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 70 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/#p-fcc8ca).",
